    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>Does c# have its own version of the java \"synchronized\" keyword? </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>No. In C#, you explicitly <code>lock</code> resources that you want to work on synchronously across asynchronous threads. <code>lock</code> opens a block; it doesn't work on method level.</p>\n\n<p>However, the underlying mechanism is similar since <code>lock</code> works by invoking <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/de0542zz.aspx\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Monitor.Enter</code></a> (and subsequently <code>Monitor.Exit</code>) on the runtime. Java works the same way, according to the <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/essential/concurrency/locksync.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Sun documentation</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
